commit_message:
Fix handling of request/response body for Python 3

In Python 3 request/response body is represented as `bytes`. This commit
adds implicit decoding from/to bytes before parsing json from it. Also
the same problem was fixed for the tests: for example, parsing response
from simulate_request requires decoding it to text string.

Change-Id: I0d210a9bc4e3f24b4440588c96e7c06ca2411b64
Partially-implements: blueprint py3k-support

subject: Modify install_rally.sh to install under BSDs
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-05-26 11:20:01.000000000', 'files': ['install_rally.sh'], 'message': 'Modify install_rally.sh to install under BSDs

The sed command (line 138) responsible for setting the database
connection string in the configuration file of Rally, is only GNU sed
compatible. The BSD systems (ex. FreeBSD, OS X) use a different sed
implementation. The in-place editing differs in these two versions. This
commit modifies the sed command in a way to be compatible for both
implementations.
It creates a temporary file and sends the output of sed to that file,
and then it replaces the original file with the temporary one. It is
actually what the --in-place switch of GNU sed does in the background
[1].

[1] http://www.gnu.org/software/sed/manual/sed.html

Change-Id: Idef71121416c1c6c5d70ab6e041f89a7b441b1f9
'}]
commit_message:
Modify install_rally.sh to install under BSDs

The sed command (line 138) responsible for setting the database
connection string in the configuration file of Rally, is only GNU sed
compatible. The BSD systems (ex. FreeBSD, OS X) use a different sed
implementation. The in-place editing differs in these two versions. This
commit modifies the sed command in a way to be compatible for both
implementations.
It creates a temporary file and sends the output of sed to that file,
and then it replaces the original file with the temporary one. It is
actually what the --in-place switch of GNU sed does in the background
[1].

[1] http://www.gnu.org/software/sed/manual/sed.html

Change-Id: Idef71121416c1c6c5d70ab6e041f89a7b441b1f9

revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2014-05-29 13:38:58.000000000', 'files': ['marconiclient/queues/v1/cli.py', 'marconiclient/queues/cli.py', 'setup.cfg'], 'message': "Initial support for openstack-client

This patch adds the initial support for the common openstack client. In
order to use it, it is necessary to:

1. Install the common openstack client
2. Install Marconi's client library

Some examples:

    $  openstack queue list --limit 3
    $  openstack queue create myqueue
    $  openstack queue delete myqueue

The above assumes keystone is installed and has an endpoint configured
for marconi. In order to bypass this in a non-keystone based deployment,
the user can pass Marconi's url manually:

    $  openstack --os-token test --os-url http://127.0.0.1:8888 queue list

Environment variables are also supported, pls refer to the openstack
common client documentation.

Change-Id: I262e42a73e46149cb16e32f9a25b787433f6790e
"}]
commit_message:
Initial support for openstack-client

This patch adds the initial support for the common openstack client. In
order to use it, it is necessary to:

1. Install the common openstack client
2. Install Marconi's client library

Some examples:

    $  openstack queue list --limit 3
    $  openstack queue create myqueue
    $  openstack queue delete myqueue

The above assumes keystone is installed and has an endpoint configured
for marconi. In order to bypass this in a non-keystone based deployment,
the user can pass Marconi's url manually:

    $  openstack --os-token test --os-url http://127.0.0.1:8888 queue list

Environment variables are also supported, pls refer to the openstack
common client documentation.

Change-Id: I262e42a73e46149cb16e32f9a25b787433f6790e

commit_message:
Make neutron-db-manage available for Metaplugin

Multiple plugins (include metaplugin itself) are active when
using metaplugin. It is necessary to do upgrade/downgrade
DB tables for each plugin.
This patch adds plugins used under metaplugin to 'active_plugins'
parameter passed to migration scripts.

Multiple plugins under metaplugin may create/drop a same table
(ex. securitygroups) in different scripts. (It occurs because
time introduced each plugin is different.)
This patch adds checking existence of table and make not to
create/drop a table if the table is already created/droped.

A script which handles a table which is common for multiple
plugins should use
'from neutron.db.migration.alembic_migrations import meta_op as op'
instead of
'from alembic import op'
It is necessary to do same thing in future scripts. Is there
any good substitute fix ?

Restriction:
neutron-db-manage does not work with offline mode for metaplugin.

Closes-Bug: #1300002
Change-Id: Ib9db9908430748ecacb27d5b5b06d6153c3d9e5f
